Definition.WordDefinition: Sac \Sac\, n. [See {Sake}, {Soc}.] (O.Eng. Law) The privilege formerly enjoyed by the lord of a manor, of holding courts, trying causes, and imposing fines. --Cowell. [1913 Webster]

Dictionary.Name: The Collaborative International Dictionary of English v.0.44

Definition.WordDefinition:
Sac \Sac\ (s[a^]k), n. [F., fr. L. saccus a sack. See {Sack} a bag.] 1. See 2d {Sack}. [1913 Webster]
2. (Biol.) A cavity, bag, or receptacle, usually containing fluid, and either closed, or opening into another cavity to the exterior; a sack. [1913 Webster]

Dictionary.Name: The Collaborative International Dictionary of English v.0.44

Definition.WordDefinition: Sacs \Sacs\ (s[add]ks), n. pl.; sing. {Sac}. (Ethnol.) A tribe of Indians, which, together with the Foxes, formerly occupied the region about Green Bay, Wisconsin. [Written also {Sauks}.] [1913 Webster]
